        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The 36ArH+(1-0) (617.525 GHz) line observed by Herschel SPIRE appears to peak in the vicinity of the target H2 knot structure.  Structures within the region are typically 1-4 arcsec in extent in the 2.12 um images and are measured to have red shift velocities of typically 100-150 km/s; in agreement with the measured displacement of the 36ArH+(1-0) line in the SPIRE spectrum.  As the velocities are not certain and because we also wish to detect the 38ArH+(1-0) (616.649 GHz) line, we will undertake a spectral scan from a frequency below 616.649 to one above 617.525 GHz taking as a representative frequency the measured one in the SPIRE spectrum – i.e. 617.220 GHz.  All sensitivity calculations are carried out at this frequency.  The scan range we have requested takes us from the 38ArH+(1-0) red shifted by ~200 km/s (~400 MHz at this frequency)  to just above the rest frequency of the 36ArH+(1-0) line.   We do not know the intrinsic width of the lines but would estimate them to be ~7 km/s.  There is velocity dispersion between knots and we wish to measure the line centres and widths of the detected lines with sufficient accuracy to clearly identify which knots are giving rise to the ArH+ production.  We have therefore requested a spectral resolution of 1.9 km/s using spectral averaging.
The peak line strength measured at low spectral resolution in the large SPIRE beam is ~ 1 Jy.  We believe this arises from the target association of H2 knots lying within the beam of SPIRE. The extent of the H2 knot association is ~5x2”.  We have requested 0.5 arcsec spatial resolution within a single Band 9 FoV (~10 arcsec) centred on this knot association which allows us to clearly detect the ArH+ emission from the knots whilst avoiding “over resolving” the region leading to a loss of sensitivity per beam.  On the assumption that the whole emission arises from the 5x2” area, the spatial dilution will be ~40x lower per ALMA beam at worst. However the 1 Jy seen by SPIRE is within a spectral resolution element equivalent to 700 km/s.  Loh et al (2012) used a medium resolution spectrometer (~100 km/s) to observe the H2 lines and did not resolve them.  The lines are clearly much narrower than 100 km/s and adopting a width of 7 km/s, as might be expected given they most likely arise in the skins of the knots, we can therefore expect the peak fluxes to be at least 100x greater.  There may be more than one velocity component so we adopt a lower figure as a conservative estimate.  We estimate that taking into account both the spatial dilution and the decreased line width the line strength per ALMA beam will be a minimum of 1.75 Jy/beam.  
We request 35 mJy sensitivity at 616.649 GHz giving 1.22 h on source time with 3 km/s bandwidth.  This gives 46 mJy at 617.22 GHz and 54 mJy at 617.525 GHz giving a high probability of detecting the 36ArH+ with a good SNR even though the (1-0) line is close to an atmospheric water feature.   The 38ArH+(1-0) line is expected to be ~5x fainter based on Solar isotopic ratios: 35 mJy sensitivity will allow us to detect the line at &gt;5-sigma under the most conservative assumptions.   The source red shift means that the 36ArH+(1-0) observed frequency is on the wing of the feature and under best observing conditions we anticipate achieving an excellent SNR allowing us to determine the detailed velocity structure in the line.
Detailed imaging of the 36ArH+ emission is desirable but not essential.  That is we do not anticipate requiring full recovery of all spatial scales within the single FoV and u-v coverage is not an issue.  For this project our intention is to confirm the presence of both 36ArH+ and 38ArH+ in the H2 knot structures.   Determination of the strength of the two lines in this situation will allow us to make the first determination of the 38Ar/36Ar ratio in a supernova remnant and probe the detailed chemistry that leads to the presence of ArH+. 
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
